WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.040 --> 00:00:04.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:18.370 --> 00:00:20.570
&gt;&gt; Betsy Peterson: We'll get
this show on the road now.

00:00:20.570 --> 00:00:24.460
And for those of you who have
been to other events here today,

00:00:24.460 --> 00:00:27.530
you'll probably hear some
of the same verbiage.

00:00:27.530 --> 00:00:28.880
So my apologies.

00:00:28.880 --> 00:00:30.480
At any rate, hello.

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:31.780
I'm Betsy Peterson.

00:00:31.780 --> 00:00:34.460
I'm the Director of the
American Folklife Center here

00:00:34.460 --> 00:00:36.120
at the Library of Congress.

00:00:36.120 --> 00:00:40.110
And I'd like to welcome everyone
here to the latest presentation

00:00:40.110 --> 00:00:43.290
of our Benjamin Botkin
Lecture Series.

00:00:43.290 --> 00:00:46.710
The Botkin Series allows
the American Folklife Center

00:00:46.710 --> 00:00:49.010
to highlight the work
of leading scholars

00:00:49.010 --> 00:00:50.510
in the disciplines of folklore.

00:00:50.510 --> 00:00:52.150
Ethnomusicology.

00:00:52.150 --> 00:00:53.450
Oral history.

00:00:53.450 --> 00:00:54.940
And cultural heritage.

00:00:54.940 --> 00:00:57.610
While also allowing us to
enhance the collections

00:00:57.610 --> 00:00:59.390
of the American Folklife Center.

00:00:59.390 --> 00:01:01.170
For the center in the library,

00:01:01.170 --> 00:01:03.650
the Botkin lectures
form an important facet

00:01:03.650 --> 00:01:06.140
of our acquisition activities.

00:01:06.140 --> 00:01:09.560
And by that I mean each lecture
is videotaped and becomes part

00:01:09.560 --> 00:01:12.450
of the permanent collections
here at the center.

00:01:12.450 --> 00:01:16.000
In addition, the lectures
are later posted as webcasts

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:17.820
on the library's website.

00:01:17.820 --> 00:01:20.680
Where they will be
available for viewing for,

00:01:20.680 --> 00:01:22.770
to Internet patrons
throughout the world.

00:01:22.770 --> 00:01:24.700
And also for future generations.

00:01:24.700 --> 00:01:27.520
So now, if you do
have a cell phone

00:01:27.520 --> 00:01:30.040
that is on, please turn it off.

00:01:30.040 --> 00:01:32.190
And we will be most
appreciative.

00:01:32.190 --> 00:01:35.030
Today I have the honor

00:01:35.030 --> 00:01:39.130
of introducing the distinguished
ethnomusicologist Deborah Wong.

00:01:39.130 --> 00:01:42.370
Dr. Wong, who is a professor
of music at the University

00:01:42.370 --> 00:01:46.000
of California, Riverside, is
well-known for her research

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:49.510
on the musics of Thailand
and Asian America.

00:01:49.510 --> 00:01:53.070
She began her studies at the
University of Pennsylvania.

00:01:53.070 --> 00:01:55.390
Where she started as a
student of anthropology

00:01:55.390 --> 00:01:59.680
and music before continuing
on to earn an MA and Ph.D.

00:01:59.680 --> 00:02:03.410
in ethnomusicology from
the University of Michigan.

00:02:03.410 --> 00:02:07.440
She's taught at UCR since 1996.

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:10.270
And has been deeply
involved with the Society

00:02:10.270 --> 00:02:14.280
for Ethnomusicology for the
whole duration of that time.

00:02:14.280 --> 00:02:17.930
Which is the premiere
scholarly society

00:02:17.930 --> 00:02:20.850
for ethnomusicology
in the United States.

00:02:20.850 --> 00:02:25.280
In addition to serving terms
on the SEM board and council,

00:02:25.280 --> 00:02:28.220
she has also served as
coeditor of the newsletter.

00:02:28.220 --> 00:02:31.420
And she was one of the
founders of the SEM committee

00:02:31.420 --> 00:02:33.100
on the status of women.

00:02:33.100 --> 00:02:39.420
And has also served as SEM's
president from 2007 to 2009.

00:02:39.420 --> 00:02:42.930
Professor Wong is also active
in numerous other scholarly

00:02:42.930 --> 00:02:45.760
and public sector
cultural organizations.

00:02:45.760 --> 00:02:48.250
She has served as board
chair for the Alliance

00:02:48.250 --> 00:02:50.320
of California Traditional Arts.

00:02:50.320 --> 00:02:52.990
And is currently a member
of the advisory board

00:02:52.990 --> 00:02:56.070
of Smithsonian Folkways
recordings.

00:02:56.070 --> 00:02:58.820
Throughout all of this,
Asian-American issues

00:02:58.820 --> 00:03:02.320
and activities have always
been a priority for Dr. Wong.

00:03:02.320 --> 00:03:04.990
She's the author of
numerous publications.

00:03:04.990 --> 00:03:08.720
Including the influential books
"Sounding the Center, History

00:03:08.720 --> 00:03:11.500
and Aesthetics in
Thai Buddhist Ritual."

00:03:11.500 --> 00:03:14.630
Which address ritual
performance and its implications

00:03:14.630 --> 00:03:18.610
for the cultural politics of
Thai court music and dance.

00:03:18.610 --> 00:03:22.480
And "Speak it Louder,
Asian-Americans making music."

00:03:22.480 --> 00:03:25.760
Which focused on
music, race and identity

00:03:25.760 --> 00:03:29.140
in Southeast Asian immigrant
communities in the Bay Area.

00:03:29.140 --> 00:03:30.680
Including some wonderful
research

00:03:30.680 --> 00:03:33.020
on Asian-American hip-hop.

00:03:33.020 --> 00:03:36.800
Most recently, for
today's Botkin lecture,

00:03:36.800 --> 00:03:42.300
Professor Wong has been studying
Japanese-American taiko drumming

00:03:42.300 --> 00:03:44.010
since 1997.

00:03:44.010 --> 00:03:47.260
And is a member of Satori
Daiko, the performing group

00:03:47.260 --> 00:03:49.870
of the Taiko Center
of Los Angeles.

00:03:49.870 --> 00:03:54.420
So we're delighted today to
have her join us and present us

00:03:54.420 --> 00:03:58.900
with a lecture on taiko drumming
in Asian-American Los Angeles.

00:03:58.900 --> 00:04:01.510
So please welcome Dr. Wong.

