Here we go.

00:13:23.270 --> 00:14:44.190
[ Drum Music ]

00:14:44.190 --> 00:14:46.540
So you're seeing,
these are two temples

00:14:46.540 --> 00:14:48.940
in the greater L.A. area.

00:14:48.940 --> 00:14:50.550
This is at the finish line

00:14:50.550 --> 00:14:52.740
of the L.A. Marathon
a couple years ago.

00:14:52.740 --> 00:14:56.470
Downtown L.A. And this is in
Little Tokyo on First Street.

00:14:56.470 --> 00:14:59.020
Anybody from, any
Japanese-American

00:14:59.020 --> 00:15:02.010
from L.A. would immediately
go, oh, that's First Street.

00:15:02.010 --> 00:15:04.260
So, yeah, you're seeing a
lot of young players; right?

00:15:04.260 --> 00:15:06.320
But you're also seeing
multigenerational groups.

00:15:06.320 --> 00:15:09.460
Which is part of the magic of
taiko, in my humble opinion,

00:15:09.460 --> 00:15:10.960
is to play with people often

00:15:10.960 --> 00:15:13.110
from three different generations
all in the same group.

00:15:13.110 --> 00:15:14.440
It's really cool.

00:15:14.440 --> 00:15:16.460
[ Video Playing ]

00:15:16.460 --> 00:15:18.090
There we go, sorry.

00:15:18.090 --> 00:15:23.170
Here's an example of one,
what we call first generation,

00:15:23.170 --> 00:15:26.300
arguably second generation
taiko player in North America.

00:15:26.300 --> 00:15:27.700
This is Kenny Endo.

00:15:27.700 --> 00:15:31.540
The most recent picture of him
is up here on the upper right.

00:15:31.540 --> 00:15:34.220
He's been playing taiko
for just over 40 years.

00:15:34.220 --> 00:15:38.090
He just celebrated his 40th
anniversary of taiko playing.

00:15:38.090 --> 00:15:40.680
He's from Los Angeles.

00:15:40.680 --> 00:15:43.780
He's Sansei, he's third
generation Japanese-American.

00:15:43.780 --> 00:15:47.190
He started playing
taiko in the 1970s.

00:15:47.190 --> 00:15:48.490
Which is, give or take,

00:15:48.490 --> 00:15:50.250
when taiko took off
in the United States.

00:15:50.250 --> 00:15:52.510
He studied in Japan.

00:15:52.510 --> 00:15:55.840
And he's lived in Honolulu for
some decades at this point.

00:15:55.840 --> 00:15:57.880
And is the founder and director

00:15:57.880 --> 00:15:59.870
of the Taiko Center
of the Pacific there.

00:15:59.870 --> 00:16:01.500
So you're seeing
photos of him here

00:16:01.500 --> 00:16:06.230
from about three different
decades of his life.

00:16:06.230 --> 00:16:09.560
Here he is in his first
few years of playing taiko.

00:16:09.560 --> 00:16:12.720
And my point here, looking at
one individual for a moment,

00:16:12.720 --> 00:16:17.460
is to say that, again,
the politics of taiko

00:16:17.460 --> 00:16:19.680
or the political significance

00:16:19.680 --> 00:16:22.160
of taiko may not always
be right out in front.

00:16:22.160 --> 00:16:26.230
It may not be people, you
know, wearing political buttons

00:16:26.230 --> 00:16:27.530
on their costumes; right?

00:16:27.530 --> 00:16:28.830
It's probably not
going to be that.

00:16:28.830 --> 00:16:32.270
The politics and meaning
of taiko are very deep,

00:16:32.270 --> 00:16:35.830
run very deep and are
not always articulated.

00:16:35.830 --> 00:16:38.300
Kenny is not going to be
the first one to tell you,

00:16:38.300 --> 00:16:40.800
and I use his name because
he's a friend of mine.

00:16:40.800 --> 00:16:42.100
His first name.

00:16:42.100 --> 00:16:45.180
He's not going to tell you, oh,
yeah, I became a taiko player

00:16:45.180 --> 00:16:46.480
through the Asian-American
movement.

00:16:46.480 --> 00:16:49.610
That's not how he's going to
explain himself, give or take.

00:16:49.610 --> 00:16:52.960
But, in fact, that is how he
got started back in the day.

00:16:52.960 --> 00:16:56.690
Manzanar is one of the Japanese
American internment camps.

00:16:56.690 --> 00:16:58.880
It's the one closest
to Los Angeles

00:16:58.880 --> 00:17:01.290
where a lot of LAJA's got sent.

00:17:01.290 --> 00:17:05.970
The Pilgrimage is something that
got started, in fact, in 1975.

00:17:05.970 --> 00:17:09.890
And this was politicized
Japanese-American who's said,

00:17:09.890 --> 00:17:12.200
we need to work on
redress and reparations.

00:17:12.200 --> 00:17:13.600
And we need to mark the camps.

00:17:13.600 --> 00:17:17.420
It was not a national park
at that point in time; right?

00:17:17.420 --> 00:17:20.620
They started going just
themselves to the sites

00:17:20.620 --> 00:17:21.920
of these former camps.

00:17:21.920 --> 00:17:26.650
And holding, you know, meetings
and made rituals, you know,

00:17:26.650 --> 00:17:30.850
to go with cultural and
political memory for the camps.

00:17:30.850 --> 00:17:33.460
This is Kenny and my teacher
Reverend Tom Karye [assumed

00:17:33.460 --> 00:17:36.890
spelling] at the first
Manzanar pilgrimage in 1975.

00:17:36.890 --> 00:17:38.190
There's Kenny.

00:17:38.190 --> 00:17:39.490
And look at these drums.

00:17:39.490 --> 00:17:42.270
This drum is from Reverend
Tom's father's temple.

00:17:42.270 --> 00:17:44.960
A Zen, Buddhist Japanese temple.

00:17:44.960 --> 00:17:50.660
This is a wine barrel that's
been made into a taiko.

00:17:50.660 --> 00:17:51.960
And not very well.

00:17:51.960 --> 00:17:54.060
You can kind of, I can see that,
you know, it's kind of uneven.

00:17:54.060 --> 00:17:56.020
It's very homemade looking.

00:17:56.020 --> 00:17:59.160
That's Kenny, you know, 1975.

00:17:59.160 --> 00:18:00.790
This is how he started
playing taiko.

00:18:00.790 --> 00:18:03.340
He didn't actually have
a teacher at that point.

00:18:03.340 --> 00:18:06.720
There was only kind of sort
of one or two other teachers

00:18:06.720 --> 00:18:08.820
for taiko in the U.S.
at that point in time.

00:18:08.820 --> 00:18:13.640
Here's more evidence of where
Kenny was at that point in time.

00:18:13.640 --> 00:18:15.880
We're now up to 1978.

00:18:15.880 --> 00:18:17.180
There he is.

00:18:17.180 --> 00:18:19.910
This is an Asian-American
music group called Warriors

00:18:19.910 --> 00:18:22.950
of the Rainbow led
by Nobuko Miyamoto.

00:18:22.950 --> 00:18:24.250
Still very active.

00:18:24.250 --> 00:18:26.480
I'm going to tell you more
about her as I go along.

00:18:26.480 --> 00:18:28.980
Here they are in an all
Asian-American band.

00:18:28.980 --> 00:18:31.760
You know, very much sort of
putting themselves out there

00:18:31.760 --> 00:18:34.850
as radical Asian-Americans
at that point in time.

00:18:34.850 --> 00:18:36.150
And there's Kenny.

00:18:36.150 --> 00:18:38.980
With his taiko, playing
with them.

00:18:40.570 --> 00:18:42.940
So the question is
like why taiko?

00:18:42.940 --> 00:18:47.560
Why were these young,
mostly Sansei being drawn

00:18:47.560 --> 00:18:52.160
to taiko rather than to
other Japanese cultural

00:18:52.160 --> 00:18:53.460
or arts forms; right?

00:18:53.460 --> 00:18:54.760
Because there are many.

00:18:54.760 --> 00:18:56.400
And they were also
in the United States.

00:18:56.400 --> 00:18:58.250
Why not sumo?

00:18:58.250 --> 00:18:59.890
Why not Zen archery?

00:18:59.890 --> 00:19:02.030
Why not flower arranging; right?

00:19:02.030 --> 00:19:03.840
There's a lot of
other cultural forms

00:19:03.840 --> 00:19:07.480
that Japanese-Americans
could have turned towards.

00:19:07.480 --> 00:19:10.120
My argument always is
that, as a musicologist,

00:19:10.120 --> 00:19:15.750
is that it's never arbitrary
what people turn to in terms

00:19:15.750 --> 00:19:20.470
of performance and culture
to speak to their needs.

00:19:20.470 --> 00:19:21.770
To address their needs.

00:19:21.770 --> 00:19:25.000
To allow them to
explore their own needs

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:26.500
and vision for the world; right?

00:19:26.500 --> 00:19:28.240
It's never arbitrary.

00:19:28.240 --> 00:19:31.330
I think that folks
turn to taiko,

00:19:31.330 --> 00:19:32.740
and it's not just my opinion.

00:19:32.740 --> 00:19:34.080
People have told me this.

00:19:34.080 --> 00:19:36.550
Because taiko is
about being heard.

00:19:36.550 --> 00:19:38.740
It's so loud, after all.

00:19:38.740 --> 00:19:40.330
It's about being heard.

00:19:40.330 --> 00:19:43.030
When taiko's going on anywhere
nearby, that's, you know,

00:19:43.030 --> 00:19:44.330
that's all you can hear.

00:19:44.330 --> 00:19:45.990
And you can feel it
for heaven's sake.

00:19:45.990 --> 00:19:48.780
I mean, the vibrations
literally travel.

00:19:48.780 --> 00:19:50.220
It's about being seen.

00:19:50.220 --> 00:19:54.390
And Asian-American visibility
is simply one of the conditions

00:19:54.390 --> 00:19:55.960
of being Asian-American, is

00:19:55.960 --> 00:19:58.130
that you're often
regarded as invisible.

00:19:58.130 --> 00:19:59.430
You are not seen.

00:19:59.430 --> 00:20:00.730
You are not heard.

00:20:00.730 --> 00:20:02.030
You are not regarded.

00:20:02.030 --> 00:20:03.720
And, finally, taiko
is about being strong.

00:20:03.720 --> 00:20:08.460
Because, although you can play,
any kind of body and any kind

00:20:08.460 --> 00:20:10.070
of ability can play taiko.

00:20:10.070 --> 00:20:15.570
It does posit a body that has
certain kinds of strength in it.

00:20:15.570 --> 00:20:17.650
And, in fact, to put it
the other way around.

00:20:17.650 --> 00:20:19.100
Taiko creates a strong body

00:20:19.100 --> 00:20:21.160
in really interesting
and important ways.

00:20:21.160 --> 00:20:25.220
So my argument is that taiko
spoke to young Asian-Americans

00:20:25.220 --> 00:20:26.550
at that the point in time.

00:20:26.550 --> 00:20:29.710
And to a great extent still
does for those reasons.

00:20:29.710 --> 00:20:31.010
For those reasons.

00:20:31.010 --> 00:20:33.540
I mean flower arranging
is lovely.

00:20:33.540 --> 00:20:36.280
But it doesn't serve
our needs, you know,

00:20:36.280 --> 00:20:38.650
in quite the same ways; right?

00:20:38.650 --> 00:20:40.180
That's my argument.

00:20:40.180 --> 00:20:47.720
Hi. This is the founder of
taiko in the United States.

00:20:47.720 --> 00:20:49.520
And I'm not going to
get all technical here.

00:20:49.520 --> 00:20:51.620
But by taiko, I am referring

00:20:51.620 --> 00:20:54.530
to a particular performance
form known in Japanese

00:20:54.530 --> 00:20:56.270
as kumi-daiko or group taiko.

00:20:56.270 --> 00:20:58.550
Meaning a whole bunch of
people playing a whole bunch

00:20:58.550 --> 00:21:02.020
of different sized
taiko drums together.

00:21:02.020 --> 00:21:06.450
Okay. Seiichi Tanaka emigrated
from Japan to the U.S. in 1968.

00:21:06.450 --> 00:21:11.330
In 1969, he created his
own taiko school, a dojo.

00:21:11.330 --> 00:21:13.800
And created the San
Francisco Taiko Dojo.

00:21:13.800 --> 00:21:16.260
Which is still alive
and well and active.

00:21:16.260 --> 00:21:18.620
And very, very important
in our scene.

00:21:18.620 --> 00:21:23.070
He's regarded as the founder of
kumi-daiko in the United States.

00:21:23.070 --> 00:21:24.370
In North America really.

00:21:24.370 --> 00:21:25.670
And here he is.

00:21:25.670 --> 00:21:28.170
You know, very, very, very
early photograph of him,

00:21:28.170 --> 00:21:30.790
famously playing at the
San Francisco Cherry

00:21:30.790 --> 00:21:33.090
Blossom Festival.

00:21:34.500 --> 00:21:38.270
Now, this group, which you
should absolutely, you know,

00:21:38.270 --> 00:21:40.780
go see them perform if
you ever have the chance.

00:21:40.780 --> 00:21:42.080
Because they're amazing.

00:21:42.080 --> 00:21:45.160
They have a very
particular kind of profile.

00:21:45.160 --> 00:21:50.330
They're known thanks to
Tanaka Sensei's values

00:21:50.330 --> 00:21:52.170
and methods for teaching.

00:21:52.170 --> 00:21:54.870
This group is known for
being way disciplined

00:21:54.870 --> 00:21:58.670
for supporting a certain
kind of powerful playing.

00:21:58.670 --> 00:22:01.510
Sometimes it's called power
taiko, as a matter of fact.

00:22:01.510 --> 00:22:05.870
The group itself is known for
being explicitly hierarchical

00:22:05.870 --> 00:22:08.110
in its social arrangement.

00:22:08.110 --> 00:22:10.590
And it's also known
for having a very

00:22:10.590 --> 00:22:13.270
"traditional" male teacher
who calls the shots.

00:22:13.270 --> 00:22:14.570
Makes the rules.

00:22:14.570 --> 00:22:15.870
You do what he says, you know.

00:22:15.870 --> 00:22:17.340
It's a sensei model in short.

00:22:17.340 --> 00:22:20.650
And it works beautifully
for this group.

00:22:20.650 --> 00:22:24.880
And Tanaka Sensei
has created many

00:22:24.880 --> 00:22:27.600
of the second generation groups.

00:22:27.600 --> 00:22:29.860
That is, he didn't do
it himself personally.

00:22:29.860 --> 00:22:33.680
But many of his original
students from the 1970s and 80s,

00:22:33.680 --> 00:22:36.830
then eventually went off and
created their own groups.

00:22:36.830 --> 00:22:39.050
Carrying forward
some of his ideas

00:22:39.050 --> 00:22:40.650
and playing techniques; right?

00:22:40.650 --> 00:22:44.430
So his impact on the
North American taiko scene

00:22:44.430 --> 00:22:45.740
is profound.

00:22:45.740 --> 00:22:47.220
Absolutely profound.

00:22:47.220 --> 00:22:51.490
And he did receive NEA
National Heritage Award

00:22:51.490 --> 00:22:53.650
about 15 years ago.

00:22:53.650 --> 00:22:55.810
Something like that, yeah.

00:22:55.810 --> 00:22:58.270
Yeah, in recognition of that.

00:22:58.270 --> 00:23:02.220
Some recent work being done
within the taiko community

00:23:02.220 --> 00:23:06.020
in the United States has
suggested that any taiko player

00:23:06.020 --> 00:23:07.580
in Canada or the United States

00:23:07.580 --> 00:23:12.700
and possibly further away
has no more than six degrees

00:23:12.700 --> 00:23:15.580
of separation from
Tanaka Sensei.

00:23:15.580 --> 00:23:16.880
And you know what?

00:23:16.880 --> 00:23:18.180
When you start talking
to people,

00:23:18.180 --> 00:23:19.480
you find out almost right away

00:23:19.480 --> 00:23:22.040
that it's usually
fewer than six degrees.

00:23:22.040 --> 00:23:24.500
You know, it's often two
or three degrees; right?

00:23:24.500 --> 00:23:26.520
Right? Mark's nodding, yeah.

00:23:26.520 --> 00:23:30.010
Yeah. So the particular
article that I found about this,

00:23:30.010 --> 00:23:32.140
you know, has all
these great diagrams.

00:23:32.140 --> 00:23:33.590
Like the one you're looking at.

00:23:33.590 --> 00:23:36.030
And taiko players love to
look at this kind of stuff.

00:23:36.030 --> 00:23:39.230
Because it literally maps
out our social relationships

00:23:39.230 --> 00:23:40.530
to one another; right?

00:23:40.530 --> 00:23:42.590
And lineages, if you will.

00:23:42.590 --> 00:23:45.070
So what I'm going to
focus on from here

00:23:45.070 --> 00:23:49.080
on are three particular
groups and individuals.

00:23:49.080 --> 00:23:52.520
They are, you know, just the
tip of the iceberg; right?

00:23:52.520 --> 00:23:54.940
And I didn't choose them
because they're like, you know,

00:23:54.940 --> 00:23:58.820
famous as much as they suggest
different ways of playing taiko.

00:23:58.820 --> 00:24:01.380
And different kinds
of values that they,

00:24:01.380 --> 00:24:03.630
different reasons
for playing taiko.

00:24:03.630 --> 00:24:05.510
So I'm going to talk
about Kinnara Taiko

00:24:05.510 --> 00:24:07.020
and then TAIKOPROJECT.

00:24:07.020 --> 00:24:10.740
And then FandangObon at the end.

00:24:10.740 --> 00:24:13.440
So let me start with
Kinnara Taiko.

00:24:13.440 --> 00:24:16.370
They are known as
taiko pioneers.

00:24:16.370 --> 00:24:19.520
And that term "pioneer," I
can't say that I'm fond of it.

00:24:19.520 --> 00:24:21.350
Because it suggests the
kind of, you know, what?

00:24:21.350 --> 00:24:22.880
Settler colonialism; right?

00:24:22.880 --> 00:24:25.870
But it is the term that's used

00:24:25.870 --> 00:24:28.900
within the North American
taiko community to suggest

00:24:28.900 --> 00:24:32.860
that we can recognize the
founding generation, as it were.

00:24:32.860 --> 00:24:35.810
And so along with Tanaka Sensei
say who is often regarded

00:24:35.810 --> 00:24:39.730
as being like the only
first gen pioneer.

00:24:39.730 --> 00:24:42.930
I would argue that Kinnara Taiko
was the other first generation

00:24:42.930 --> 00:24:44.230
pioneer group.

00:24:44.230 --> 00:24:47.190
They were founded like, you
know, virtually the same year

00:24:47.190 --> 00:24:49.740
as San Francisco Taiko Dojo.

00:24:49.740 --> 00:24:51.420
But they were located

00:24:51.420 --> 00:24:55.380
at a Jodoshinshu
temple in Los Angeles.

00:24:55.380 --> 00:24:56.840
Senshin Buddhist Temple.

00:24:56.840 --> 00:24:58.370
Where I spend a lot of time.

00:24:58.370 --> 00:25:01.480
And what they did
through Reverend Mas who's

00:25:01.480 --> 00:25:03.020
in the back there.

00:25:03.020 --> 00:25:06.690
Reverend Mas Kodani has
explicitly positioned taiko

00:25:06.690 --> 00:25:11.540
playing as hogaku, as a
form of Buddhist practice.

00:25:11.540 --> 00:25:13.020
Certainly a lot of fun to play,

00:25:13.020 --> 00:25:16.490
but not being played
only for fun.

00:25:16.490 --> 00:25:20.070
You know, as a form
of Buddhist devotion.

00:25:20.070 --> 00:25:21.680
And the structure of the group,

00:25:21.680 --> 00:25:25.900
thanks to Reverend Mas was very
explicitly nonhierarchical.

00:25:25.900 --> 00:25:27.810
Which make it's profoundly
different

00:25:27.810 --> 00:25:30.440
from San Francisco Taiko Dojo.

00:25:30.440 --> 00:25:33.500
And, in fact, egalitarian
in how they acted stuff out.

00:25:33.500 --> 00:25:35.070
How they made decisions
together.

00:25:35.070 --> 00:25:36.370
It was consensus driven.

00:25:36.370 --> 00:25:39.240
There were apparently hours
and hours of conversation

00:25:39.240 --> 00:25:40.990
to make any kind of
decision together; right?

00:25:40.990 --> 00:25:42.290
You know, this kind of thing.

00:25:42.290 --> 00:25:46.010
So this is a great photograph
of a lot of those folks

00:25:46.010 --> 00:25:47.310
from that first generation.

00:25:47.310 --> 00:25:49.170
And many of them are
still around and still

00:25:49.170 --> 00:25:51.030
at Senshin Buddhist Temple.

00:25:51.030 --> 00:25:54.110
I want you to see
just a little slice

00:25:54.110 --> 00:25:55.990
of them playing back in the day.

00:25:55.990 --> 00:25:57.660
This is a documentary
that was made

00:25:57.660 --> 00:26:00.960
in 1975 titled "Cruisin'
J-Town."

00:26:00.960 --> 00:26:02.910
J-Town is Japan Town.

00:26:02.910 --> 00:26:06.050
It's filmed in Little Tokyo
in L.A. And you're going

00:26:06.050 --> 00:26:10.070
to see first Johnny Mori, who
is another noted taiko player

00:26:10.070 --> 00:26:12.830
in L.A. You're going to
see him as a young man sort

00:26:12.830 --> 00:26:16.580
of making his way through
the Asian-American movement.

00:26:16.580 --> 00:26:18.450
And going to Amerasia Bookstore.

00:26:18.450 --> 00:26:20.200
And then you're going
to see him wind

00:26:20.200 --> 00:26:23.260
up at Senshin Buddhist Temple
playing with Kinnara Taiko.

00:26:23.260 --> 00:26:25.510
And he's still with Kinnara.

00:26:25.510 --> 00:26:44.730
[ Music ]

00:26:44.730 --> 00:26:47.660
&gt;&gt; I look in the mirror, I'm
traditional Japanese looking.

00:26:47.660 --> 00:26:49.240
I mean, I got slanted eyes.

00:26:49.240 --> 00:26:50.820
The black hair; right?

00:26:50.820 --> 00:26:52.940
So every day I look,
you know, it's Japanese.

00:26:52.940 --> 00:26:55.640
But yet, on the other hand,
I'm Japanese-American.

00:26:55.640 --> 00:26:59.700
I can relate more to a black
or a Chicano than I can

00:26:59.700 --> 00:27:01.380
to a person from Japan.

00:27:01.380 --> 00:27:04.100
So that's why, you know,
creating an Asian-American thing

00:27:04.100 --> 00:27:05.770
that I could feel
comfortable with, you know,

00:27:05.770 --> 00:27:08.270
I think it's pretty important.

00:27:08.270 --> 00:27:09.570
&gt;&gt; Hey.

00:27:09.570 --> 00:27:11.350
&gt;&gt; Hey, what's happening?

00:27:11.350 --> 00:27:14.050
Working here in the bookstore,
it's an atmosphere where I'm

00:27:14.050 --> 00:27:16.750
in contact with our history
here in the United States.

00:27:16.750 --> 00:27:19.390
And it started to dawn on me

00:27:19.390 --> 00:27:21.740
that music was another
expression

00:27:21.740 --> 00:27:23.970
that I could possibly
use to get into as far

00:27:23.970 --> 00:27:26.510
as an Asian-American
identity kind of thing.

00:27:26.510 --> 00:27:56.370
[ Drum Music ]

00:27:56.370 --> 00:27:57.720
&gt;&gt; Dr. Deborah Wong:
Historic footage, this.

00:27:57.720 --> 00:28:01.120
And it's filmed at
Senshin Buddhist Temple.

00:28:01.120 --> 00:28:02.420
And guess what?

00:28:02.420 --> 00:28:04.370
Tomorrow is their
annual Obon Festival.

00:28:04.370 --> 00:28:06.630
And I'm going to fly
home tomorrow and land

00:28:06.630 --> 00:28:10.720
at Ontario Airport and then
drive straight to Senshin, yeah.

00:28:10.720 --> 00:28:13.200
I love their Obon ritual.

00:28:13.200 --> 00:28:17.230
And the last thing that
happens at the Senshin Obon is

00:28:17.230 --> 00:28:18.530
that Kinnara always plays.

00:28:18.530 --> 00:28:21.050
It's about nine or ten
o'clock at night at that point.

00:28:21.050 --> 00:28:23.340
And they play, as you know,

00:28:23.340 --> 00:28:27.450
horaku or hogaku, as
Buddhists worship.

00:28:27.450 --> 00:28:30.170
I mean, it looks just
like taiko you'd anywhere.

00:28:30.170 --> 00:28:32.700
But it's purpose is different.

00:28:32.700 --> 00:28:34.000
So that's one group.

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:35.430
And they're still
very much around.

00:28:35.430 --> 00:28:37.120
They're, many of
them are now older.

00:28:37.120 --> 00:28:39.200
But they've brought
in younger members.

00:28:39.200 --> 00:28:40.640
The group continues.

00:28:40.640 --> 00:28:42.160
Its spirit, its philosophy,

00:28:42.160 --> 00:28:46.820
its values remain very
securely in place.

00:28:46.820 --> 00:28:48.120
So they're there.

00:28:48.120 --> 00:28:49.420
They're part of the scene.

00:28:49.420 --> 00:28:50.720
They're respected.

00:28:50.720 --> 00:28:52.020
They're known.

00:28:52.020 --> 00:28:53.320
They're recognized.

00:28:53.320 --> 00:28:54.620
They're pioneers.

00:28:54.620 --> 00:28:55.920
I want to turn to
the second group now.

00:28:55.920 --> 00:28:57.220
And that's TAIKOPROJECT.

00:28:57.220 --> 00:28:58.520
And that is how they call
themselves, TAIKOPROJECT.

00:28:58.520 --> 00:28:59.820
One word. All capital letters.

00:28:59.820 --> 00:29:04.570
Okay. And this is one could say
a third generation taiko group.

00:29:04.570 --> 00:29:07.040
And it's mostly,
when they started,

00:29:07.040 --> 00:29:10.620
over 10 years 15 years
ago, they were in fact all

00:29:10.620 --> 00:29:12.650
in their 20s at that point.

00:29:12.650 --> 00:29:14.410
And this is part of what's going

00:29:14.410 --> 00:29:16.150
on with taiko more
broadly; right?

00:29:16.150 --> 00:29:20.210
Is that taiko is
growing, is expanding.

00:29:20.210 --> 00:29:22.620
There's literally more
groups, more taiko players.

00:29:22.620 --> 00:29:25.320
More infrastructure
than there once was.

00:29:25.320 --> 00:29:27.320
And what usually happens

00:29:27.320 --> 00:29:29.180
when you have more people
doing things, right,

00:29:29.180 --> 00:29:32.590
is that they begin to divide
off into different scenes.

00:29:32.590 --> 00:29:35.710
Different kinds of ways
of doing things; right?

00:29:35.710 --> 00:29:37.250
So literally the
taiko community,

00:29:37.250 --> 00:29:40.600
if we can still call it that,
is now more and more diverse

00:29:40.600 --> 00:29:42.910
in terms of how they do things.

00:29:42.910 --> 00:29:44.210
And who they do things with.

00:29:44.210 --> 00:29:47.430
And so like regional taiko
is now more of a thing

00:29:47.430 --> 00:29:48.970
than it once was, for instance.

00:29:48.970 --> 00:29:51.390
But these, the scene is
still connected in very,

00:29:51.390 --> 00:29:53.770
very interesting ways.

00:29:53.770 --> 00:29:55.980
This is all about the
rising generation.

00:29:55.980 --> 00:29:59.640
Any tradition faces this.

00:29:59.640 --> 00:30:02.710
What happens when new
generations become part

00:30:02.710 --> 00:30:05.040
of that tradition?

00:30:05.040 --> 00:30:06.340
It all depends; right?

00:30:06.340 --> 00:30:10.290
Sometimes things are very
carefully kept the same,

00:30:10.290 --> 00:30:11.740
whatever that might mean.

00:30:11.740 --> 00:30:14.950
But often it means that
things begin to change.

00:30:14.950 --> 00:30:17.500
Again, responding to the
conditions of the time,

00:30:17.500 --> 00:30:18.910
of the moment, of the place.

00:30:18.910 --> 00:30:21.850
So the rising generation
of taiko players,

00:30:21.850 --> 00:30:24.540
and I think actually there's
two rising generations

00:30:24.540 --> 00:30:25.840
at this point.

00:30:25.840 --> 00:30:28.110
Many of them were trained
in collegiate groups.

00:30:28.110 --> 00:30:32.320
Taiko clubs on university
and college campuses.

00:30:32.320 --> 00:30:34.970
Some of them also came up
through community groups.

00:30:34.970 --> 00:30:37.710
Some of them are doing both,
which is very interesting.

00:30:37.710 --> 00:30:42.000
A number of these folks are
very aware of taiko history.

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:43.300
Others are not at all.

00:30:43.300 --> 00:30:45.700
If they just joined taiko as
a club on campus, you know,

00:30:45.700 --> 00:30:47.020
it's they're having
a great time.

00:30:47.020 --> 00:30:48.320
They're learning a lot,

00:30:48.320 --> 00:30:49.620
but history is the
least of it; right?

00:30:49.620 --> 00:30:53.160
Many of these groups, because
these are young players,

00:30:53.160 --> 00:30:54.780
they're in their teens and 20s.

00:30:54.780 --> 00:30:57.950
They have like these
amazing bodies; right?

00:30:57.950 --> 00:31:00.820
And, you know, they're
brains are just like firing.

00:31:00.820 --> 00:31:02.430
And they create these
pieces that are

00:31:02.430 --> 00:31:05.790
like incredibly complicated
with lots of different sections.

00:31:05.790 --> 00:31:09.280
And, you know, complex meters.

00:31:09.280 --> 00:31:11.110
And, you know, all kinds
of stuff like this.

00:31:11.110 --> 00:31:12.690
And some of them very much want

00:31:12.690 --> 00:31:16.270
to become professional
taiko players at this point.

00:31:16.270 --> 00:31:18.920
Here's some lovely
photos of some

00:31:18.920 --> 00:31:21.090
of the leaders now
actually pushing 40.

00:31:21.090 --> 00:31:24.750
Some of the first rising gen.
Michelle Fuji up on the right.

00:31:24.750 --> 00:31:28.020
Bryan Yamami, who
founded TAIKOPROJECT.

00:31:28.020 --> 00:31:30.680
And these are members
of the On Ensemble.

00:31:30.680 --> 00:31:32.730
Maz Baba. Kris Bergstrom.

00:31:32.730 --> 00:31:34.100
Shoji Kameda.

00:31:34.100 --> 00:31:39.770
This is TAIKOPROJECT, a photo
that's now a decade old taken

00:31:39.770 --> 00:31:41.350
in Little Tokyo.

00:31:41.350 --> 00:31:43.960
Actually a couple blocks away.

00:31:43.960 --> 00:31:47.020
But, you know, this absolutely,
this like sums up the spirit

00:31:47.020 --> 00:31:48.560
of TAIKOPROJECT, you know.

00:31:48.560 --> 00:31:50.750
They're all in their 20s pretty
much at that point in time

00:31:50.750 --> 00:31:53.830
with all the energy
and enthusiasm; right?

00:31:53.830 --> 00:31:55.260
A lot of their pictures are

00:31:55.260 --> 00:31:57.130
of them leaping into
the air; right?

00:31:57.130 --> 00:31:58.430
This kind of thing.

00:31:58.430 --> 00:31:59.730
It's a great photo.

00:31:59.730 --> 00:32:01.630
And I might say that Bryan's
also been very careful

00:32:01.630 --> 00:32:05.240
to have really professional
standards brought to everything

00:32:05.240 --> 00:32:06.540
that TAIKOPROJECT does.

00:32:06.540 --> 00:32:07.840
Including PR.

00:32:07.840 --> 00:32:12.100
So TAIKOPROJECT, it's a group
of third gen taiko players.

00:32:12.100 --> 00:32:14.660
Yeah, they're all
about energy and kind

00:32:14.660 --> 00:32:16.030
of a playfulness as well.

00:32:16.030 --> 00:32:19.090
Which is not typical of like
Japanese type of groups,

00:32:19.090 --> 00:32:20.820
if one can generalize.

00:32:20.820 --> 00:32:22.440
They're often, you
know, like smiling.

00:32:22.440 --> 00:32:23.740
And, you know, there's laughter

00:32:23.740 --> 00:32:25.510
and jokes built into
their pieces.

00:32:25.510 --> 00:32:28.380
They are very aware of
their Japanese roots.

00:32:28.380 --> 00:32:30.490
But they are also
unapologetically

00:32:30.490 --> 00:32:33.030
and openly American
in what they're up to.

00:32:33.030 --> 00:32:34.330
And the membership

00:32:34.330 --> 00:32:37.310
of TAIKOPROJECT is almost
entirely Asian-American.

00:32:37.310 --> 00:32:39.940
Not just Japanese-American,
but also, you know, Chinese.

00:32:39.940 --> 00:32:41.360
Korean. Filipino.

00:32:41.360 --> 00:32:43.760
You know, different
Asian-Americans.

00:32:43.760 --> 00:32:46.680
There are a few non-Asian
Americans, but not many.

00:32:46.680 --> 00:32:48.800
Another photo of them.

00:32:48.800 --> 00:32:51.910
With Bryan Yamami and the
founder in the middle there.

00:32:53.070 --> 00:32:55.030
And you need to see them play.

00:32:55.030 --> 00:32:57.900
This is one of their
very well-known pieces.

00:32:57.900 --> 00:33:01.040
And, again, in sort
of counterpoint

00:33:01.040 --> 00:33:05.430
to Japanese taiko values,
Shoji Kameda, then a member

00:33:05.430 --> 00:33:09.240
of TAIKOPROJECT, wrote
this piece explicitly

00:33:09.240 --> 00:33:10.540
as an open-source piece.

00:33:10.540 --> 00:33:12.480
Open to any taiko group to play.

00:33:12.480 --> 00:33:13.780
No ownership.

00:33:13.780 --> 00:33:15.430
Not tied just to TAIKOPROJECT.

00:33:15.430 --> 00:33:18.470
But a piece that he
framed as being a gift

00:33:18.470 --> 00:33:20.680
to the taiko community.

00:33:20.680 --> 00:33:21.980
An omiyage.

00:33:21.980 --> 00:33:23.280
It means gift.

00:33:23.280 --> 00:33:25.060
Actually, it means a kind
of gift that you bring back

00:33:25.060 --> 00:33:26.820
when you've been
traveling somewhere.

00:33:26.820 --> 00:33:29.730
And you get little souvenirs
to bring home and give

00:33:29.730 --> 00:33:31.170
to your friends and family.

00:33:31.170 --> 00:33:33.960
That's what an omiyage is, yeah.

00:33:33.960 --> 00:33:36.510
This is part of a
much longer piece.

00:33:36.510 --> 00:35:18.310
[ Drum Music ]

00:35:18.310 --> 00:35:20.420
In, wearing the orange shirt

00:35:20.420 --> 00:35:23.570
in the center there,
that's Yuta Kato.

00:35:23.570 --> 00:35:25.060
An amazing performer.

00:35:25.060 --> 00:35:27.000
Now has risen to a real
position of leadership

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:29.410
in the greater North
American taiko community.

00:35:29.410 --> 00:35:32.880
And you can hear at one point
some of the other players

00:35:32.880 --> 00:35:35.120
on stage yell out Yuta.

00:35:35.120 --> 00:35:37.440
You know, as he took
off on his solo; right?

00:35:37.440 --> 00:35:39.670
One of the other things

00:35:39.670 --> 00:35:44.960
that TAIKOPROJECT has done very
adroitly is to insert themselves

00:35:44.960 --> 00:35:48.470
into the greater L.A.
entertainment industry.

00:35:48.470 --> 00:35:50.160
We are after all in L.A.

00:35:50.160 --> 00:35:51.870
; right? It's about La-La Land.

00:35:51.870 --> 00:35:53.960
It's about, you know,
all the opportunities

00:35:53.960 --> 00:35:55.390
that the film industry,

00:35:55.390 --> 00:35:58.900
the entertainment
industry generally offers.

00:35:58.900 --> 00:36:04.060
And Bryan Yamami, the director
and founder of TAIKOPROJECT

00:36:04.060 --> 00:36:07.140
in very well-known ways
has made TAIKOPROJECT,

00:36:07.140 --> 00:36:08.440
has put them out there.

00:36:08.440 --> 00:36:10.040
And you find them in a
number of commercials.

00:36:10.040 --> 00:36:12.510
You see them playing at
industry conferences.

00:36:12.510 --> 00:36:14.180
You know, and they also play

00:36:14.180 --> 00:36:16.800
in community settings,
to be very clear.

00:36:16.800 --> 00:36:18.670
They're playing in a
lot of different places.

00:36:18.670 --> 00:36:20.990
But they're also cultivating
this kind of thing.

00:36:20.990 --> 00:36:24.360
2005, they played in this
one minute commercial

00:36:24.360 --> 00:36:26.510
for the Mitsubishi Eclipse.

00:36:26.510 --> 00:37:19.720
[ Drum Music ]

00:37:19.720 --> 00:37:23.170
&gt;&gt; Introducing the all new
2006 Mitsubishi Eclipse.

00:37:23.170 --> 00:37:27.950
Available six speed,
263 horse, MIVEC V6.

00:37:27.950 --> 00:37:29.250
&gt;&gt; Dr. Deborah Wong:
You get the idea.

00:37:29.250 --> 00:37:31.970
I have very mixed feelings
about this commercial.

00:37:31.970 --> 00:37:33.850
I think it's really slick.

00:37:33.850 --> 00:37:36.010
It's really you know,
it's well done.

00:37:36.010 --> 00:37:40.340
But it also feeds directly into
like really tired ideas about,

00:37:40.340 --> 00:37:43.200
you know, Orientalist
dragon lady, you know,

00:37:43.200 --> 00:37:45.510
Asian babe in a red dress
kind of stuff, you know.

00:37:45.510 --> 00:37:47.700
And, or I should, it
wouldn't even be Asian; right?

00:37:47.700 --> 00:37:50.250
It would be Oriental
babe in a red dress.

00:37:50.250 --> 00:37:53.900
And there's more to be
said about this commercial.

00:37:53.900 --> 00:37:56.180
I mean, one is that the
folks who are looking

00:37:56.180 --> 00:37:58.630
for taiko players were
making the commercial.

00:37:58.630 --> 00:38:00.590
And they went out into
the greater L.A. area.

00:38:00.590 --> 00:38:02.230
Lots of taiko groups; right?

00:38:02.230 --> 00:38:04.590
And they auditioned a whole
lot of different taiko players

00:38:04.590 --> 00:38:06.650
for this commercial
back in the day.

00:38:06.650 --> 00:38:08.990
They also auditioned
members of my group.

00:38:08.990 --> 00:38:11.750
And they looked at us,
and we were a bunch of at

00:38:11.750 --> 00:38:13.900
that point sort of
middle-aged, you know,

00:38:13.900 --> 00:38:16.990
not necessarily beautiful
looking people

00:38:16.990 --> 00:38:19.160
who played taiko very well.

00:38:19.160 --> 00:38:22.040
But they looked at us and were
like, okay, thanks very much.

00:38:22.040 --> 00:38:25.470
And then they went onto to the
TAIKOPROJECT and said, oh, wow,

00:38:25.470 --> 00:38:27.110
look at these young
women; right?

00:38:27.110 --> 00:38:29.660
You know, and so you end
up with this commercial.

00:38:29.660 --> 00:38:33.060
Which I think shows
off the playing ability

00:38:33.060 --> 00:38:35.830
of at least the young
women in TAIKOPROJECT.

00:38:35.830 --> 00:38:39.070
But it feeds into other
kinds of cultural tropes

00:38:39.070 --> 00:38:40.900
that I am tired of
seeing; right?

00:38:40.900 --> 00:38:45.170
As I said, in 2016,
a census was done.

00:38:45.170 --> 00:38:48.110
A voluntary census
of taiko players.

00:38:48.110 --> 00:38:51.190
And we learned at that
point that a majority

00:38:51.190 --> 00:38:53.080
of taiko players
are, in fact, women.

00:38:53.080 --> 00:38:55.460
And Asian-American
women at that.

00:38:55.460 --> 00:38:57.900
And a number of us
had anecdotally

00:38:57.900 --> 00:39:00.610
and just impressionistically
known that for a long time.

00:39:00.610 --> 00:39:03.480
But the numbers were confirmed
at this point in time.

00:39:03.480 --> 00:39:07.900
And we also began to realize
that our own way of thinking

00:39:07.900 --> 00:39:09.750
and talking about
who plays taiko

00:39:09.750 --> 00:39:13.090
and why was becoming
complicated.

00:39:13.090 --> 00:39:15.340
And has been actually
for a while.

00:39:15.340 --> 00:39:18.450
One is the matter,
is taiko Japanese?

00:39:18.450 --> 00:39:20.710
Some groups always say,
well, this is Japanese taiko.

00:39:20.710 --> 00:39:24.440
Even if all of them are
from Chicago, you know.

00:39:24.440 --> 00:39:27.580
Is taiko really a
Japanese-American form?

00:39:27.580 --> 00:39:29.690
Is it now more broadly
Asian-American.

00:39:29.690 --> 00:39:31.170
Which would be my argument.

00:39:31.170 --> 00:39:33.700
Or is it, in fact, for
everyone, you know?

00:39:33.700 --> 00:39:36.060
And that's where things
get dicy, in my opinion.

00:39:36.060 --> 00:39:38.860
I think any music at some
level could be argued

00:39:38.860 --> 00:39:40.980
as being for everyone.

00:39:40.980 --> 00:39:43.490
You know, but what does it
mean when suddenly any kind

00:39:43.490 --> 00:39:46.820
of music becomes
ownable by anyone?

00:39:46.820 --> 00:39:49.400
Could be participated
in by anyone?

00:39:49.400 --> 00:39:50.700
What does that mean?

00:39:50.700 --> 00:39:52.760
You know, what happens
with global spread

00:39:52.760 --> 00:39:54.060
of certain traditions?

00:39:54.060 --> 00:39:56.950
What does it mean when every
jazz band has a didgeridoo

00:39:56.950 --> 00:39:58.250
in the middle?

00:39:58.250 --> 00:39:59.550
You know, this kind of thing.

00:39:59.550 --> 00:40:02.190
So I have questions about what
it means to be for everyone.

00:40:02.190 --> 00:40:04.230
And that might be
where taiko's going.

00:40:04.230 --> 00:40:05.530
But, for instance,

00:40:05.530 --> 00:40:07.730
in the Midwest these are
two different taiko groups

00:40:07.730 --> 00:40:11.980
in Indiana and Minneapolis.

00:40:11.980 --> 00:40:15.140
What does it mean when
this becomes the face

00:40:15.140 --> 00:40:16.480
of taiko players?

00:40:16.480 --> 00:40:18.010
And let me be very clear,

00:40:18.010 --> 00:40:19.950
I'm not saying white
people shouldn't play taiko.

00:40:19.950 --> 00:40:21.250
I am not saying that.

00:40:21.250 --> 00:40:22.550
I am not saying that.

00:40:22.550 --> 00:40:23.850
I'm not thinking it either.

00:40:23.850 --> 00:40:27.140
But I am saying that
race and gender

00:40:27.140 --> 00:40:32.150
and community location is
significant in any form

00:40:32.150 --> 00:40:35.130
of performance in terms of what
are the stories being told?

00:40:35.130 --> 00:40:37.100
What is the narrative
being served?

00:40:37.100 --> 00:40:38.400
And by whom?

00:40:38.400 --> 00:40:41.410
For whom? So taiko is changing.

00:40:41.410 --> 00:40:42.710
It's changing fast.

00:40:42.710 --> 00:40:44.050
And this is TAIKOPROJECT.

00:40:44.050 --> 00:40:47.210
It remains, you know, 90
percent Asian-American

00:40:47.210 --> 00:40:48.510
in it's personnel.

00:40:48.510 --> 00:40:52.610
And very much connected to the
Japanese-American community.

00:40:52.610 --> 00:40:56.440
Let me turn to my final
example, FandangObon.

00:40:56.440 --> 00:41:00.170
And this is a form, a project.

00:41:00.170 --> 00:41:03.270
It's really a project that is

00:41:03.270 --> 00:41:07.980
about connecting two very
specific communities in L.A.,

00:41:07.980 --> 00:41:10.050
in the greater L.A. area.

00:41:10.050 --> 00:41:11.890
It's about activism.

00:41:11.890 --> 00:41:15.050
It has everything to do
with the fact that more

00:41:15.050 --> 00:41:18.670
than once interethnic
violence and tension

00:41:18.670 --> 00:41:21.050
between different
neighborhoods and communities

00:41:21.050 --> 00:41:25.650
in L.A. burst open
in very violent ways.

00:41:25.650 --> 00:41:27.360
Very controversial ways.

00:41:27.360 --> 00:41:30.050
And so the L.A. uprising
or riots

00:41:30.050 --> 00:41:34.520
of 1992 was not the first
time that this happened.

00:41:34.520 --> 00:41:37.040
So I'm just offering
you a little reminder

00:41:37.040 --> 00:41:40.860
that this is part of the
landscape of Los Angeles

00:41:40.860 --> 00:41:44.160
and has been for a long time.

00:41:44.160 --> 00:41:49.430
So FandangObon is primarily
these three amazing thinker,

00:41:49.430 --> 00:41:51.980
performers, activists.

00:41:51.980 --> 00:41:54.540
I cannot get enough time
with these three people.

00:41:54.540 --> 00:41:57.170
On the left we have
Quetzal Flores.

00:41:57.170 --> 00:41:58.470
We have Martha Gonzales.

00:41:58.470 --> 00:42:00.450
And the two of them with some
other folks make up the band,

00:42:00.450 --> 00:42:03.420
Quetzal, which is all
it's in Chicago a lot.

00:42:03.420 --> 00:42:06.740
And then Nobuko Miyamoto
on the right here.

00:42:06.740 --> 00:42:08.510
The three of them
are close friends.

00:42:08.510 --> 00:42:12.810
And they created the FandangObon
project together five years ago.

00:42:12.810 --> 00:42:17.060
Fandango is central to
a very specific area

00:42:17.060 --> 00:42:19.750
of Mexico of the Veracruz area.

00:42:19.750 --> 00:42:23.780
Fandango, it's a very
explicitly participatory form

00:42:23.780 --> 00:42:26.490
of performance and
community gathering.

00:42:26.490 --> 00:42:29.600
Obon is the Japanese
and Japanese-American,

00:42:29.600 --> 00:42:31.330
it's now a summer festival.

00:42:31.330 --> 00:42:33.690
Originally a time when, part

00:42:33.690 --> 00:42:37.420
of the Japanese Buddhists
recognition of ancestors.

00:42:37.420 --> 00:42:40.030
Some say a time when the souls

00:42:40.030 --> 00:42:42.470
of the departed come
back and visit us.

00:42:42.470 --> 00:42:46.760
So both of these forms,
Fandango and Obon are dynamic.

00:42:46.760 --> 00:42:48.580
Alive. Well.

00:42:48.580 --> 00:42:51.270
Not endangered in their
communities; right?

00:42:51.270 --> 00:42:53.050
These are dynamic traditions.

00:42:53.050 --> 00:42:54.650
They're flourishing even.

00:42:54.650 --> 00:42:57.130
Both of them have
these similarities

00:42:57.130 --> 00:42:58.840
in their emphasis
on participation.

00:42:58.840 --> 00:43:02.150
That you don't need to be like
a professional or trained person

00:43:02.150 --> 00:43:03.660
to participate in them.

00:43:03.660 --> 00:43:05.880
They're meant for
anybody to be part of.

00:43:05.880 --> 00:43:07.960
They're focused on community.

00:43:07.960 --> 00:43:11.140
And both of them are deeply
informed by the politics

00:43:11.140 --> 00:43:13.620
in the United States
of the 1960s and 70s.

00:43:13.620 --> 00:43:15.870
When like the Chicano
movement got going.

00:43:15.870 --> 00:43:19.130
The Asian-American
movement got going.

00:43:19.130 --> 00:43:21.990
This is part of both
scenes as well.

00:43:21.990 --> 00:43:30.790
So a glimpse of Obon in L.A.
This is higashi [phonetic]

00:43:30.790 --> 00:43:34.280
with taiko in the middle.

00:43:34.280 --> 00:43:38.340
The dances are participated
in by hundreds

00:43:38.340 --> 00:43:39.640
and hundreds of people.

00:43:39.640 --> 00:43:40.940
This is the time of year

00:43:40.940 --> 00:43:43.760
where every weekend a different
temple is hosting Obon.

00:43:43.760 --> 00:43:47.220
And people go from one temple to
another over the entire summer.

00:43:47.220 --> 00:43:48.520
So hundreds of people.

00:43:48.520 --> 00:43:52.770
Some temples there's over 1,000
people dancing altogether.

00:43:52.770 --> 00:43:55.950
Fandango. This photograph is

00:43:55.950 --> 00:43:58.350
