00:48:31.060 --> 00:48:35.020
But what's going on here
is that the East L.A.,

00:48:35.020 --> 00:48:38.940
traditionally Mexican-American,
Chicanx neighborhood

00:48:38.940 --> 00:48:43.650
and Little Tokyo, right
across the L.A. River

00:48:43.650 --> 00:48:47.030
from East L.A. This
project brought those two

00:48:47.030 --> 00:48:48.330
neighborhoods together.

00:48:48.330 --> 00:48:49.630
Very intentionally; right?

00:48:49.630 --> 00:48:52.830
This was a result of months and
months and months of planning

00:48:52.830 --> 00:48:54.400
and discussion and meetings.

00:48:54.400 --> 00:48:57.280
Martha and Quetzal
being deeply embedded

00:48:57.280 --> 00:48:59.650
in the East L.A.
Chicanx community.

00:48:59.650 --> 00:49:03.150
Nobuko and others and Reverend
Mas here being, you know,

00:49:03.150 --> 00:49:04.930
key figures in Little Tokyo.

00:49:04.930 --> 00:49:07.630
So they took the elements of
both of those traditions, right,

00:49:07.630 --> 00:49:08.980
and they put them together.

00:49:08.980 --> 00:49:11.100
Fandango and Bon Odori.

00:49:11.100 --> 00:49:17.020
This re-embeds taiko in the kind
of, you know, big ritual dance

00:49:17.020 --> 00:49:21.220
and more tradition that it
actually is most profoundly

00:49:21.220 --> 00:49:22.520
embedded in.

00:49:22.520 --> 00:49:25.740
It took the dance
steps from Bon Odori

00:49:25.740 --> 00:49:28.280
and injected moves
from Fandango.

00:49:28.280 --> 00:49:29.860
Some of the foot movements.

00:49:29.860 --> 00:49:33.530
Other, you know, this is
Guacamaya is from Fandango.

00:49:33.530 --> 00:49:35.900
It's a very careful attempt

00:49:35.900 --> 00:49:39.040
from culture barriers
to create a new form.

00:49:39.040 --> 00:49:42.020
Not meant to be like fusion
or anything like that.

00:49:42.020 --> 00:49:45.770
But meant to represent
qualities of both traditions.

00:49:45.770 --> 00:49:47.970
And meant to be carried forward.

00:49:47.970 --> 00:49:49.710
We're now in the fifth
year of FandangObon.

00:49:49.710 --> 00:49:52.430
It is being performed
at many different Obon

00:49:52.430 --> 00:49:55.680
in the greater L.A. area
this summer, as it has been

00:49:55.680 --> 00:49:56.980
for the past four years.

00:49:56.980 --> 00:50:00.570
So this is the amazing
circle of performers

00:50:00.570 --> 00:50:03.110
that created the
project together.

00:50:03.110 --> 00:50:06.500
And as Reverend Mas says,
this shouldn't be a fusion.

00:50:06.500 --> 00:50:09.620
Because a lot of
intercultural talk is often

00:50:09.620 --> 00:50:10.920
at that level, you know.

00:50:10.920 --> 00:50:12.220
It's fusion.

00:50:12.220 --> 00:50:13.520
It's like, you know,
fusion cuisine, you know.

00:50:13.520 --> 00:50:16.480
Like where you throw some
soy sauce and some nam pla

00:50:16.480 --> 00:50:19.210
and some lime and some adobo.

00:50:19.210 --> 00:50:20.840
And, you know, we
put it all together.

00:50:20.840 --> 00:50:22.140
And it's great, you know.

00:50:22.140 --> 00:50:25.030
And that's kind of the extent
of the thinking; right?

00:50:25.030 --> 00:50:27.750
Reverend Mas is like,
no, it's not fusion.

00:50:27.750 --> 00:50:29.380
It's not fusion.

00:50:29.380 --> 00:50:32.160
It's putting different elements
together, and it's doing it

00:50:32.160 --> 00:50:34.270
in a very thoughtful
and intentional way.

00:50:34.270 --> 00:50:36.210
It's creating a conversation.

00:50:36.210 --> 00:50:38.350
A conversation, yeah.

00:50:38.350 --> 00:50:40.560
This is the mission.

00:50:40.560 --> 00:50:42.350
They've had to apply
for grants to get some

00:50:42.350 --> 00:50:43.650
of this off of the ground.

00:50:43.650 --> 00:50:46.460
You often have to have
a mission statement

00:50:46.460 --> 00:50:47.830
when you apply for
grants, you know.

00:50:47.830 --> 00:50:50.560
So they had chances where
they were able to sort

00:50:50.560 --> 00:50:52.430
or articulate what
they were up to.

00:50:52.430 --> 00:50:56.860
And these are the bottom lines
for the FandangObon project.

00:50:56.860 --> 00:50:58.730
Kind of musical dialogue.

00:50:58.730 --> 00:51:00.440
Open cultural borders.

00:51:00.440 --> 00:51:03.500
It's not about trying to
make those borders dissolve

00:51:03.500 --> 00:51:04.800
or go away.

00:51:04.800 --> 00:51:06.100
Because that's magical thinking.

00:51:06.100 --> 00:51:07.850
It's about trying
to open the borders,

00:51:07.850 --> 00:51:09.720
sometimes only temporarily,

00:51:09.720 --> 00:51:11.890
between diverse Angeleno
communities.

00:51:11.890 --> 00:51:13.360
Can ritual circle dance,

00:51:13.360 --> 00:51:15.620
these are both ritual
traditions; right?

00:51:15.620 --> 00:51:17.750
Can ritual circle dance help us

00:51:17.750 --> 00:51:20.320
to imagine a new
vision for Los Angeles?

00:51:20.320 --> 00:51:22.020
And I would argue yes.

00:51:22.020 --> 00:51:23.830
I believe it has been happening

00:51:23.830 --> 00:51:26.830
through this project
among other ways.

00:51:26.830 --> 00:51:31.980
