tradition of making taiko
out of wine barrels.

00:55:40.000 --> 00:55:42.080
Literally buying
them from wineries.

00:55:42.080 --> 00:55:43.830
Disassembling them.

00:55:43.830 --> 00:55:47.180
Extensive techniques went into
how to put them back together

00:55:47.180 --> 00:55:49.030
into really functioning taiko.

00:55:49.030 --> 00:55:50.540
And we all knew the
different places

00:55:50.540 --> 00:55:52.550
where you could buy cow hide.

00:55:52.550 --> 00:55:55.440
Cow hide. You know,
this kind of thing.

00:55:55.440 --> 00:55:58.640
And many collegiate groups,
many community groups continued

00:55:58.640 --> 00:56:00.160
to learn how to do that.

00:56:00.160 --> 00:56:03.260
And it's not only considered to
be important cultural knowledge

00:56:03.260 --> 00:56:04.710
to know how to make a taiko.

00:56:04.710 --> 00:56:06.800
But to do it communally,

00:56:06.800 --> 00:56:10.160
collectively together,
in short, you know.

00:56:10.160 --> 00:56:12.700
To get covered with
sawdust and all that stuff

00:56:12.700 --> 00:56:14.300
that goes along with it; right?

00:56:14.300 --> 00:56:16.290
This is beginning to change.

00:56:16.290 --> 00:56:20.540
Lots of folks still
make their own drums.

00:56:20.540 --> 00:56:22.970
But five years ago one

00:56:22.970 --> 00:56:26.310
of the major Japanese
taiko-making companies

00:56:26.310 --> 00:56:30.360
and families, Asano opens their
first North American store.

00:56:30.360 --> 00:56:32.390
And it's in the greater
L.A. area.

00:56:32.390 --> 00:56:34.570
It's in Torrance.

00:56:34.570 --> 00:56:38.480
Yeah, and they've
created this amazing venue

00:56:38.480 --> 00:56:39.980
where they teach classes.

00:56:39.980 --> 00:56:42.400
They have a showroom
where you can drop a lot

00:56:42.400 --> 00:56:44.220
of money on beautiful stuff.

00:56:44.220 --> 00:56:48.280
And more and more groups are
buying their drums from Asano.

00:56:48.280 --> 00:56:50.280
I'm curious about
how this is going

00:56:50.280 --> 00:56:51.610
to change the scene, you know.

00:56:51.610 --> 00:56:52.910
And some of those drums are made

00:56:52.910 --> 00:56:54.890
out of literally a
single piece of wood.

00:56:54.890 --> 00:56:57.850
You know, it's very different
from the wine barrel technique.

00:56:57.850 --> 00:57:02.470
You know, is this hauling us
back to a certain sort of,

00:57:02.470 --> 00:57:05.820
you know, Japanese-centered
way of doing things?

00:57:05.820 --> 00:57:08.140
It remains to be seen.

00:57:08.140 --> 00:57:09.440
Their stuff is expensive.

00:57:09.440 --> 00:57:11.730
So not everybody's going
to be able to buy them.

00:57:11.730 --> 00:57:14.220
So the drums are from
both here and there.

00:57:14.220 --> 00:57:16.520
Great question.

00:57:18.190 --> 00:57:19.770
&gt;&gt; Yeah, what are the difference

00:57:19.770 --> 00:57:25.170
between the Chinese drums
[inaudible], Chinese drums

00:57:25.170 --> 00:57:27.340
and the taiko you're
talking about?

00:57:27.340 --> 00:57:29.720
Because I know in
China they have,

00:57:29.720 --> 00:57:33.130
different regions
have different type

00:57:33.130 --> 00:57:37.480
of drum performance sort of.

00:57:37.480 --> 00:57:43.790
Did you see any relationship
between the two?

00:57:43.790 --> 00:57:48.200
&gt;&gt; Dr. Deborah Wong: The
simplest answer is like, no.

00:57:48.200 --> 00:57:50.650
You know, but I think one
could point to, more broadly

00:57:50.650 --> 00:57:55.080
to an East Asian arc of
percussion where some

00:57:55.080 --> 00:57:58.690
of the manufactured
techniques are similar.

00:57:58.690 --> 00:58:01.360
But the context are
pretty different.

00:58:01.360 --> 00:58:05.600
I do think, for what it's worth,
that the global phenomenon

00:58:05.600 --> 00:58:10.480
of taiko becoming popular
beyond Japan has led to, like,

00:58:10.480 --> 00:58:13.400
some Chinese drum
groups that are drawing

00:58:13.400 --> 00:58:15.880
from ideas about Japanese taiko.

00:58:15.880 --> 00:58:18.840
And, you know, now
they're playing, you know,

00:58:18.840 --> 00:58:22.080
like Lion Dance type
Chinese drumming.

00:58:22.080 --> 00:58:26.460
But with a lot of kind of
taiko moves and rhythms put in.

00:58:26.460 --> 00:58:28.320
It's very, very interesting.

00:58:28.320 --> 00:58:30.510
I mean, but the deeper
answer is that, no,

00:58:30.510 --> 00:58:32.460
they're not directly related.

00:58:32.460 --> 00:58:35.870
And, two, they're part of a
broader East Asian emphasis

00:58:35.870 --> 00:58:38.280
on certain kinds of
percussion for ritual.

00:58:38.280 --> 00:58:39.580
For ritual.

00:58:39.580 --> 00:58:40.880
&gt;&gt; Oh, yeah.

00:58:40.880 --> 00:58:43.750
I think you're talking about
more from U.S. point of view.

00:58:43.750 --> 00:58:46.850
But have you ever done
any research in China?

00:58:46.850 --> 00:58:48.510
Because I know it's
for thousands

00:58:48.510 --> 00:58:51.620
of years they have
this drum performance.

00:58:51.620 --> 00:58:52.920
I'm sure in.

00:58:52.920 --> 00:58:54.220
&gt;&gt; Dr. Deborah Wong:
This is true.

00:58:54.220 --> 00:58:56.010
&gt;&gt; In history is, you know, in
history there must be some kind

00:58:56.010 --> 00:58:57.800
of a learning from each other.

00:58:57.800 --> 00:59:01.570
Or, you know, it might
be the other way around.

00:59:01.570 --> 00:59:03.830
But I'm just throw a point here.

00:59:03.830 --> 00:59:06.890
But, you know, it's interesting
I just want to make a comment.

00:59:06.890 --> 00:59:09.880
Because yesterday I
went to Smithsonian.

00:59:09.880 --> 00:59:16.110
And the new director for
the national art museum,

00:59:16.110 --> 00:59:19.650
National Museum for
African Art, Gus Hayford.

00:59:19.650 --> 00:59:24.420
He also mentioned something
about the African drum.

00:59:24.420 --> 00:59:29.650
And the, he brought
up another perspective

00:59:29.650 --> 00:59:35.690
of this drum performance in
the history that is more like,

00:59:35.690 --> 00:59:40.770
expressed quantifiable pain.

00:59:40.770 --> 00:59:47.700
And also express hope, you know,
to manifest their sufferings.

00:59:47.700 --> 00:59:51.860
And also their hope for
more equality in history.

00:59:51.860 --> 00:59:54.640
I guess to this type

00:59:54.640 --> 00:59:57.500
of performance more
like entertainment.

00:59:57.500 --> 01:00:02.040
I'm just making comment,
you know.

01:00:02.040 --> 01:00:06.530
He said that for African drum,
it's more like, you know,

01:00:06.530 --> 01:00:08.460
almost like a code
for revolution.

01:00:08.460 --> 01:00:13.100
But in certain type of the
period during the history,

01:00:13.100 --> 01:00:17.930
that it was not allowed
for African-American.

01:00:17.930 --> 01:00:19.230
[ Multiple Speakers ]

01:00:19.230 --> 01:00:20.530
&gt;&gt; Dr. Deborah Wong: Oh, for
slaves in the United States.

01:00:20.530 --> 01:00:22.200
&gt;&gt; People to perform,
to play drums.

01:00:22.200 --> 01:00:25.920
Because it's so inspiring,
I guess.

01:00:25.920 --> 01:00:31.820
You know, it's like a
[inaudible] for revolution.

01:00:31.820 --> 01:00:33.120
That's what he commented.

01:00:33.120 --> 01:00:37.140
I'm just trying to make some
kind of connection here.

01:00:37.140 --> 01:00:38.630
&gt;&gt; Dr. Deborah Wong: Well,
you just said a whole bunch

01:00:38.630 --> 01:00:44.270
of different things, and
they're all very interesting.

01:00:44.270 --> 01:00:45.570
Yeah.

01:00:45.570 --> 01:00:46.870
[ Inaudible Comment ]

01:00:46.870 --> 01:00:48.170
Yeah. Let me put it this way.

01:00:48.170 --> 01:00:52.130
You know, if you look at sort
of music in a global context,

01:00:52.130 --> 01:00:55.320
you know, every place
has its own kinds

01:00:55.320 --> 01:00:56.790
of musical instruments.

01:00:56.790 --> 01:00:59.370
And that's like really
interesting to those of us

01:00:59.370 --> 01:01:01.060
who look at world music.

01:01:01.060 --> 01:01:03.760
It's very striking that
drums are found everywhere.

01:01:03.760 --> 01:01:06.300
And that, by that I mean, you
know, a body with some sort

01:01:06.300 --> 01:01:08.270
of membrane stretched
over the end.

01:01:08.270 --> 01:01:10.260
Which is then struck; right?

01:01:10.260 --> 01:01:12.820
That's what I mean by a drum.

01:01:12.820 --> 01:01:17.240
Again, in East Asia there are
very old traditions of drumming.

01:01:17.240 --> 01:01:21.200
Many of them connected
directly to Buddhism

01:01:21.200 --> 01:01:24.270
and in Japan's case
Shinto as well.

01:01:24.270 --> 01:01:27.360
And to original religions,
you know.

01:01:27.360 --> 01:01:29.950
Indigenous religions,
if you will.

01:01:29.950 --> 01:01:31.900
Are they directly connected?

01:01:31.900 --> 01:01:35.280
I'm just going to doggedly
say, no, they're not.

01:01:35.280 --> 01:01:37.670
Because, in fact, there's
one way of sort of looking

01:01:37.670 --> 01:01:38.970
at music around the world.

01:01:38.970 --> 01:01:41.790
Which is to say, everything
started in one place

01:01:41.790 --> 01:01:43.090
and then went to
some place else.

01:01:43.090 --> 01:01:45.720
And there's a long tradition
of saying, in east Asia,

01:01:45.720 --> 01:01:49.010
that stuff started in China, and
it moved out from there; right?

01:01:49.010 --> 01:01:50.970
And in some cases it's true.

01:01:50.970 --> 01:01:53.080
In other cases it
ends op sort of wiping

01:01:53.080 --> 01:01:56.160
out indigenous traditions
and practices.

01:01:56.160 --> 01:01:59.860
Or at least attention to
things that do originate

01:01:59.860 --> 01:02:01.420
in places outside China.

01:02:01.420 --> 01:02:03.870
So, I mean, these are
complicated questions.

01:02:03.870 --> 01:02:09.220
And to bring it full circle back
to where you ended with slaves.

01:02:09.220 --> 01:02:13.220
You know, in the African slave
trade and diaspora, yeah,

01:02:13.220 --> 01:02:18.640
percussion was regarded by slave
owners as inherently dangerous.

01:02:18.640 --> 01:02:20.550
Because it allowed
slaves to continue

01:02:20.550 --> 01:02:23.730
to practice their own religions.

01:02:23.730 --> 01:02:25.030
And points of view.

01:02:25.030 --> 01:02:26.820
And ways of coming
together communally.

01:02:26.820 --> 01:02:29.110
And that was a problem
for slave owners.

01:02:29.110 --> 01:02:30.980
Yeah. Yeah.

01:02:30.980 --> 01:02:33.240
Yeah. Yeah.

